  <subsection xml:id="subsection-transforming-between-standard-form-and-slope-intercept-form">
    <title>Transforming between Standard Form and Slope-Intercept Form</title>
    <p>
      Sometimes a linear equation arises in
      <xref ref="definition-standard-form" text="custom">standard form</xref>, but it would be
      useful to see that equation in
      <xref ref="equation-slope-intercept-form" text="custom">slope-intercept form</xref>. Or
      perhaps, vice versa.
    </p>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Change <m>2x-3y=-6</m> to slope-intercept form, and then graph it. (This is the same
          equation from <xref ref="example-graph-by-intercepts"/>).
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Since a line in slope-intercept form looks like <m>y=\ldots</m>, we will isolate <m>y</m>:
        </p>
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <p>
            <md>
              <mrow>2x-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
              <mrow>-3y\amp=-6\subtractright{2x}</mrow>
              <mrow>-3y\amp=-2x-6</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=\divideunder{-2x-6}{-3}</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=\frac{-2x}{-3}-\frac{6}{-3}</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=\frac{2}{3}x+2</mrow>
            </md>
          </p>
          <p>
            In the third line, we wrote <m>-2x-6</m> on the right side, instead of <m>-6-2x</m>. The
            only reason we did this is because we are headed to slope-intercept form, where the
            <m>x</m>-term is traditionally written first.
          </p>
        </sidebyside>
        <p>
          Now we can see that the slope is <m>\frac{2}{3}</m> and the <m>y</m>-intercept is at
          <m>(0,2)</m>. With these things found, we can graph the line using slope triangles.
        </p>
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
          <p>
            Compare this graphing method with the Graphing by Intercepts method in
            <xref ref="example-graph-by-intercepts"/>. We have more points in this graph, thus we
            can graph the line more accurately.
          </p>
          <figure>
            <caption>Graphing <m>2x-3y=-6 </m> with Slope Triangles</caption>
            <image>
              <shortdescription>
                a coordinate gris with the graph of the line 2x-3y=-6; the y-intercept is 2 and the
                slope is 2/3; slope triangles are shown along the line with a run of 3 and a rise of
                2
              </shortdescription>
              <latex-image label="standard-form-2x-3yequals-6-slope-triangles">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                  \begin{axis}[
                      width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                    ]
                    \addplot+[]{2/3*x+2};
                    \addplot[only marks,color=firstcolor]
                    coordinates{
                        (-6,-2)
                        (-3,0)
                        (0,2)
                        (3,4)
                        (6,6)
                    };
                    \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,2) (3,2)} node[pos=0.5,below] {$3$};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(3,2) (3,3.7)} node[pos=0.588,right] {$2$};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(3,4) (6,4) (6,5.7)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,2) (-3,2) (-3,0.3)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(-3,0) (-6,0) (-6,-1.7)};
                  \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
              </latex-image>
            </image>

          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-graph-standard-c-zero">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Graph <m>2x-3y=0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          First, we will try
          (and fail)
          to graph this line using its <m>x</m>- and <m>y</m>-intercepts.
        </p>
        <p>
          Trying to find the <m>x</m>-intercept:
          <md>
            <mrow>2x-3y\amp=0</mrow>
            <mrow>2x-3(\substitute{0})\amp=0</mrow>
            <mrow>2x\amp=0</mrow>
            <mrow>x\amp=0</mrow>
          </md>
          So the line's <m>x</m>-intercept is at <m>(0,0)</m>, at the origin. Hmm, the origin is
          <em>also</em> on the <m>y</m>-axis<ellipsis /> So we've also found the <m>y</m>-intercept
          even though that was not the immediate goal.
        </p>
        <p>
          Since both intercepts are the same point, there is no way to use the intercepts alone to
          graph this line. So what can be done?
        </p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" valign="top">
          <p>
            One is to convert the line equation into slope-intercept form:
            <md>
              <mrow>2x-3y\amp=0</mrow>
              <mrow>-3y\amp=0\subtractright{2x}</mrow>
              <mrow>-3y\amp=-2x</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=\divideunder{-2x}{-3}</mrow>
              <mrow>y\amp=\frac{2}{3}x</mrow>
            </md>
            So the line's slope is <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>, and we can graph the line using slope
            triangles and the intercept at <m>(0,0)</m>, as in <xref ref="figure-through-origin"/>.
          </p>

          <figure xml:id="figure-through-origin">
            <caption>Graphing <m>2x-3y=0 </m> with Slope Triangles</caption>
            <image width="47%">
              <shortdescription>
                a coordinate grid with the graph of line 2x-3y=0; The line has a y-intercept of 0
                and a slope of 2/3; slope triangles are shown along the line with a run of 3 and a
                rise of 2
              </shortdescription>
              <latex-image label="standard-form-2x-3yequals0-slope-triangles">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                  \begin{axis}[
                      width=0.47\orccaprintwidth,
                    ]
                    \addplot+[]{2/3*x};
                    \addplot[only marks,color=firstcolor] coordinates{(-6,-4) (-3,-2) (0,0) (3,2) (6,4)};
                    \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,0) (3,0)} node[pos=0.5,above] {$3$};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(3,0) (3,1.7)} node[pos=0.588,right] {$2$};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(3,2) (6,2) (6,3.7)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,0) (-3,0) (-3,-1.7)};
                    \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(-3,-2) (-6,-2) (-6,-3.7)};
                  \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
        <p>
          If <m>C=0</m> in a
          <xref ref="definition-standard-form" text="custom">standard form equation</xref>, it's
          convenient to graph it by first converting the equation to
          <xref ref="equation-slope-intercept-form" text="custom">slope-intercept form</xref>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the equation <m>y=\frac{2}{3}x+2</m> in standard form.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Once we subtract <m>\frac{2}{3}x</m> on both sides of the equation, we have
          <me>
            -\frac{2}{3}x+y=2
          </me>
          Technically,
          this equation is already in standard form <m>Ax+By=C</m>. However,
          you might like to end up with an equation that has no fractions,
          so you could multiply each side by <m>3</m>:
          <md>
            <mrow>\multiplyleft{3}\left(-\frac{2}{3}x+y\right)\amp=\multiplyleft{3}2</mrow>
            <mrow>-2x+3y\amp=6</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

