    <subexercises>
      <title>Challenge</title>
      <exercise>
        <!-- Kara's challenge problem -->
        <webwork>
          <pg-code>
            $little = random(2,10,2);
            $medium = $little+1;
            $medium2 = $medium+1;
            do {$big = random($medium2,15,1);} until ($big % $little != 0);
            $steepest = Formula("$big/$little");
            $shallowest = Formula("$little/$big");
          </pg-code>
          <introduction>
            <p>
              Fill in the variables <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m> in <m>Ax + By = C</m> with the
              numbers <m><var name="$little"/>, <var name="$medium"/></m> and
              <m><var name="$big"/></m>. You may only use each number once in each part.
            </p>
          </introduction>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                For the steepest possible slope, <m>A</m> must be <var name="$big" width="4"/>,
                <m>B</m> must be <var name="$little" width="4"/>, and <m>C</m> must be
                <var name="$medium" width="4"/>.
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                Let's put <m>Ax + By = C</m> into slope-intercept form. Then, the equation
                becomes <m>y = \frac{-A}{B}x + \frac{C}{B}</m>. To make the steepest slope
                possible, we must maximize the fraction <m>\frac{A}{B}</m>. The possibilities
                are <m>\frac{<var name="$little"/>}{<var name="$medium"/>}</m>,
                <m>\frac{<var name="$little"/>}{<var name="$big"/>}</m>,
                <m>\frac{<var name="$medium"/>}{<var name="$little"/>}</m>,
                <m>\frac{<var name="$medium"/>}{<var name="$big"/>}</m>,
                <m>\frac{<var name="$big"/>}{<var name="$little"/>}</m>,
                and <m>\frac{<var name="$big"/>}{<var name="$medium"/>}</m>. The biggest of
                these is <m>\frac{<var name="$big"/>}{<var name="$little"/>}</m>. Thus, <m>A</m>
                must equal <var name="$big"/>, <m>B</m> must equal <var name="$little"/>, and
                <m>C</m> must equal <var name="$medium"/>.
              </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
          <task>
            <statement>
              <p>
                For the shallowest possible slope, <m>A</m> must be
                <var name="$little" width="4"/>, <m>B</m> must be <var name="$big" width="4"/>,
                and <m>C</m> must be <var name="$medium" width="4"/>.
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                To make the shallowest slope possible, we must minimize the fraction
                <m>\frac{A}{B}</m>. The smallest of the possible fractions is
                <m>\frac{<var name="$little"/>}{<var name="$big"/>}</m>. Thus, <m>A</m> must
                equal <var name="$little"/>, <m>B</m> must equal <var name="$big"/>, and
                <m>C</m> must equal <var name="$medium"/>.
              </p>
            </solution>
          </task>
        </webwork>
      </exercise>
